<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-12-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="307" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d307">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/327½</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-12-07">December 7,
                                        1934</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>After reading the papers of the past three days, I am inclined to
                                think that it would be well to tell Davis, confidentially, something
                                to this effect: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“Now that the effect of denunciation by the Japanese has been
                                        made clear to Matsudaira by both the British and ourselves,
                                        we think you should do nothing further before December
                                        thirty-first, as a result <pb facs="0491" n="391" xml:id="pg_391"/> of which the Japanese could use that
                                        as a reason or a partial reason for denunciation. In other
                                        words, we are in an excellent position at the present time.
                                        Even if it involves keeping the conversations going until
                                        December thirty-first, it is worthwhile to do it in order
                                        that the whole onus of denunciation can be placed on the
                                        Japanese without giving them any excuses.”</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <p>What do you think.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D. R[<hi rend="smallcaps">oosevelt</hi>]</signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>